08524nam a22010695i 9783111186047DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831111860477 a10.1515/97831111860472doi  a(DE-B1597)645488  a(OCoLC)1394872193  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aD13 7aHIS0350002bisacsh04a907.2223/eng/2023062700aProfessional Historians in Public :bOld and New Roles Revisited /ced. by Berber Bevernage, Lutz Raphael. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 391 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Politics of Historical Thinking ,x2625-0055 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tThe Politics of Historical Thinking -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 New Roles for Professional Historians and New Public Uses of the Past -- tPart One: Histoires Engagées: A Critical Look Back -- t2 Eric Hobsbawm as a Public Champion of Cosmopolitan Universalism -- t3 Two Sides of Activist Scholarship Within UNESCO’s General History of Africa (1964–1998) -- t4 Colonial Historiography, Hindutva, and the Difficulty of Reading the Ancient Indian Historical Traditions -- tPart Two: Law and Historical Expertise -- t5 Challenges of Historical Expert Witnessing in the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia and Elsewhere -- t6 The Waitangi Tribunal and the Public Life of History -- tPart Three: Old and New Public Demands on Professional Historians -- t7 Between Discipline and Profession: Historical Studies and Their Public Relevance in Brazil -- t8 Policy-Oriented History for the EU: The Rise of a New Type of Professional Practice for Historians? -- t9 Indigenous History, Activism, and the Decolonizing University: Challenges, Opportunities, and the Struggle over the Khoisan Past in Post-apartheid South Africa -- tPart Four: Public History in New Media -- t10 Russian Public Historians in the New Media (The Case of Telegram) -- t11 Practices of Popular Science and Digital Curation in Theory of History on the Portuguese Edition of Wikipedia -- tPart Five: Perspectives: Moral, Epistemic, and Political -- t12 Historians and Human Rights Advocacy -- t13 The Politics of Memory and the Task of Historians -- t14 Languages of Legitimation and the Registers of Legitimate History -- tBiographical Notes -- tSelected Bibliography on ‘Public Uses of the Past and the Role of Professional Historians in the Public Sphere’ -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe past decades public interest in history is booming. This creates new opportunities but also challenges for professional historians. This book asks how historians deal with changing public demands for history and how these affect their professional practices, values and identities. The volume offers a great variety of detailed studies of cases where historians have applied their expertise outside the academic sphere. With contributions focusing on Latin America, Africa, Asia, the Pacific and Europe the book has a broad geographical scope. Subdivided in five sections, the book starts with a critical look back on some historians who broke with mainstream academic positions by combining their professional activities with an explicit political partisanship or social engagement. The second section focusses on the challenges historians are confronted with when entering the court room or more generally exposing their expertise to legal frameworks. The third section focuses on the effects of policy driven demands as well as direct political interventions and regulations on the historical profession. A fourth section looks at the challenges and opportunities related to the rise of new digital media. Finally several authors offer their view on normative standards that may help to better respond to new demands and to define role models for publicly engaged historians. This book aims at historians and other academics interested in public uses of history.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoriansxHistory. 0aHistoriographyxHistory. 0aPublic history. 4aEngaged history. 4aExpertise. 4aHistoriker. 4aPublic History. 7aHISTORY / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aPublic history.  aengaged history.  ahistorical expertise.1 aAttwood, Bain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBam, June, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBevernage, Berber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBevernage, Berber, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBragio Bonaldo, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Baets, Antoon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlorentino Varella, Flávia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolesnik, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicolazzi, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrović, Vladimir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaphael, Lutz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaphael, Lutz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSavelieva, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulte Nordholt, Larissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinha, Kanad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStepanov, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo